INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('PM E-DRIVE Explained: India\'s EV Subsidy Scheme After FAME II','pm-e-drive-scheme-explained','FAME II ended in March 2024. Here is how the PM E-DRIVE scheme now works, how much you can save on a two- or three-wheeler EV, and how state subsidies stack on top.','<p>The FAME II scheme, which drove much of India\'s early EV adoption, officially ended on 31 March 2024. It has been replaced by the <strong>PM E-DRIVE</strong> (Electric Drive Revolution in Innovative Vehicle Enhancement) scheme.</p><h2>How much can you save?</h2><p>Under PM E-DRIVE, electric two-wheelers receive a demand incentive of roughly <strong>&#8377;2,500 per kWh</strong> of battery capacity, capped at about &#8377;5,000 per vehicle. Three-wheelers receive substantially more. Four-wheelers are not covered by central cash incentives and instead rely on state subsidies and road-tax waivers.</p><h2>State subsidies stack on top</h2><p>States like Delhi, Gujarat, Maharashtra and Uttar Pradesh add their own incentives and, in most cases, fully waive road tax and registration for EVs. The smartest buyers stack the central PM E-DRIVE incentive, the state subsidy and the road-tax waiver together.</p><p>Use our <a href=\"/on-road-price\">On-Road Price Calculator</a> to see your real, subsidy-adjusted price by state, and the <a href=\"/subsidy-calculator\">Subsidy Calculator</a> for a full breakdown.</p>','Policy','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-26 18:22:20','1547','PM E-DRIVE Explained: India\'s EV Subsidy Scheme After FAME II | Charj.in','FAME II ended in March 2024. Here is how the PM E-DRIVE scheme now works, how much you can save on a two- or three-wheeler EV, and how state subsidies stack on top.','PM E-DRIVE, FAME II, subsidy, policy','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('Best Electric Scooters in India 2026: Range, Price & Real-World Value','best-electric-scooters-india-2026','From the Ather 450X to the Ola S1 Pro and TVS iQube, here are the electric scooters worth shortlisting in 2026 — ranked on real-world range, charging and ownership cost.','<p>India\'s electric two-wheeler market is the most competitive EV segment in the country. Here are the models worth shortlisting in 2026.</p><h2>Ather 450X</h2><p>Still the enthusiast favourite for its build quality, software and fast-charging network. The 3.7 kWh variant delivers a realistic 110&ndash;130 km.</p><h2>Ola S1 Pro</h2><p>Class-leading on-paper range and a low entry price. The Gen-2 platform improved reliability noticeably.</p><h2>TVS iQube</h2><p>The sensible, no-drama choice with strong dealer support and a roomy floorboard. The 5.1 kWh ST variant is the one to get for longer commutes.</p><p>Compare any of these side-by-side with our <a href=\"/compare\">EV comparison tool</a>, or take the <a href=\"/find-my-ev\">EV Finder quiz</a> for a personalised match.</p>','Buying Guide','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-25 18:22:20','759','Best Electric Scooters in India 2026: Range, Price & Real-World Value | Charj.in','From the Ather 450X to the Ola S1 Pro and TVS iQube, here are the electric scooters worth shortlisting in 2026 — ranked on real-world range, charging and ownership cost.','electric scooter, Ather, Ola, TVS, buying guide','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('EV vs Petrol: The Real 5-Year Cost of Ownership in India','ev-vs-petrol-5-year-cost-india','EVs cost more upfront but far less to run. We break down fuel, maintenance, insurance and resale over five years to show when an EV actually pays for itself.','<p>The sticker price is only part of the story. Over five years, the running-cost gap between an EV and an equivalent petrol vehicle is large.</p><h2>Fuel vs electricity</h2><p>A petrol scooter costs roughly &#8377;2.5&ndash;3.5 per km to run. An EV charged at home costs around &#8377;0.15&ndash;0.30 per km &mdash; often a 10x saving on energy alone.</p><h2>Maintenance</h2><p>No engine oil, no clutch, far fewer moving parts. EV servicing is typically a fraction of petrol maintenance.</p><h2>The break-even</h2><p>For most daily commuters covering 30+ km a day, an EV breaks even on its price premium within 2&ndash;3 years and saves money every year after that.</p><p>Run your own numbers with the <a href=\"/tco-calculator\">5-Year TCO Calculator</a>.</p>','Analysis','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-24 18:22:20','1028','EV vs Petrol: The Real 5-Year Cost of Ownership in India | Charj.in','EVs cost more upfront but far less to run. We break down fuel, maintenance, insurance and resale over five years to show when an EV actually pays for itself.','TCO, cost of ownership, EV vs petrol','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('ARAI vs Real-World Range: How to Read EV Range Claims','arai-vs-real-world-ev-range','The range on the brochure is rarely the range you get. Here is why ARAI/IDC figures are optimistic and how to estimate the real range you can rely on.','<p>Every EV is advertised with a headline range figure &mdash; and almost every owner gets less. Here is why.</p><h2>How the test works</h2><p>Certified range (ARAI/IDC) is measured in controlled lab conditions: moderate speeds, no AC, ideal temperature. Your commute has traffic, inclines, AC and highway speeds, all of which cut range.</p><h2>A realistic rule of thumb</h2><p>Expect <strong>70&ndash;85%</strong> of the claimed range in mixed real-world use, and less in peak summer or winter. For a scooter claiming 150 km, plan around 110&ndash;125 km.</p><p>Planning a longer trip? Use the <a href=\"/trip-planner\">Trip Charging Planner</a> and the <a href=\"/can-i-make-it\">Trip Range Check</a> before you set off.</p>','Explainer','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-23 18:22:20','1085','ARAI vs Real-World Range: How to Read EV Range Claims | Charj.in','The range on the brochure is rarely the range you get. Here is why ARAI/IDC figures are optimistic and how to estimate the real range you can rely on.','range, ARAI, real-world range, explainer','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('Home EV Charger Installation in India: Cost, Types & What to Know','home-ev-charger-installation-guide','Charging at home is the cheapest, most convenient way to run an EV. Here is what a home charger costs, what to install, and what apartment dwellers can do.','<p>Home charging turns an EV into the most convenient vehicle you can own &mdash; you leave every morning full. Here is what to know.</p><h2>What you need</h2><p>Most two-wheelers charge from a regular 5/15A socket. Cars benefit from a dedicated AC wall box (3.3&ndash;7.4 kW) installed by the manufacturer or a certified electrician.</p><h2>Typical cost</h2><p>A home AC wall box plus installation usually runs &#8377;25,000&ndash;50,000 for a car; two-wheeler owners often need nothing beyond a nearby socket.</p><h2>Living in an apartment?</h2><p>Talk to your housing society early. Many states now legally support EV charging in shared parking. See our <a href=\"/ev-for-apartment\">EV for Apartments guide</a> and the full <a href=\"/home-charger-guide\">Home Charger Guide</a>.</p>','Guide','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-22 18:22:20','830','Home EV Charger Installation in India: Cost, Types & What to Know | Charj.in','Charging at home is the cheapest, most convenient way to run an EV. Here is what a home charger costs, what to install, and what apartment dwellers can do.','home charging, charger installation, guide','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
INSERT INTO articles (`title`,`slug`,`excerpt`,`content`,`category`,`author_name`,`status`,`published_at`,`views`,`seo_title`,`seo_description`,`tags`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES ('Tata Nexon EV Long Range Review: India\'s Default Electric SUV','tata-nexon-ev-long-range-review','With a ~465 km claimed range, fast charging and a strong service network, the Nexon EV Long Range remains the benchmark mass-market electric SUV in India.','<p>The Tata Nexon EV is, for many Indian families, the EV that made an electric car feel practical. The Long Range variant is the one to buy.</p><h2>Range &amp; charging</h2><p>The 40.5 kWh pack delivers a claimed ~465 km and a realistic 330&ndash;380 km. DC fast charging takes it from 10&ndash;80% in under an hour.</p><h2>Ownership</h2><p>Tata\'s widening service and charging network is a real advantage over newer rivals, and resale has held up better than most EVs in its class.</p><h2>Verdict</h2><p>Still the safe, sensible default electric SUV. Compare it against the MG ZS EV and others with our <a href=\"/compare\">comparison tool</a>, and check the <a href=\"/on-road-price\">on-road price</a> in your state.</p>','Review','Charj.in Editorial','published','2026-06-21 18:22:20','1200','Tata Nexon EV Long Range Review: India\'s Default Electric SUV | Charj.in','With a ~465 km claimed range, fast charging and a strong service network, the Nexon EV Long Range remains the benchmark mass-market electric SUV in India.','Tata Nexon EV, review, electric SUV','2026-06-26 18:22:20','2026-06-26 18:22:20');
